name: cis-1,3-dimethylcyclopentane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The basic unit cyclopentane has a melting point of -94 degrees Celsius. Each methyl group in a molecule contributes to an increase in the melting point due to increased van der Waals forces from the larger electron cloud, which leads to better packing in the solid state. However, the cis configuration of the methyl groups on the cyclopentane will result in steric hindrance and slightly less efficient molecular packing, which would normally decrease the melting point compared to the trans isomer or a linear alkane with the same number of carbons. For cycloalkanes, each methyl group might be expected to raise the melting point by about 20 degrees Celsius, but the steric hindrance in the cis configuration might reduce the effectiveness of each methyl group to increase the melting point by about 5 degrees Celsius. Therefore, two methyl groups would add roughly 40 - 2(5) = 30 degrees Celsius. Thus, the melting point would be expected to increase from the base value of cyclopentane by about 30 degrees Celsius.
